revision.text:
'''Archedemus''' of [[Tarsus (city)|Tarsus]] ({{lang-el|Άρχέδημος ὁ Ταρσεύς}})<ref>Strabo, ''Geography'', xiv; Diogenes Laërtius, ''Lives of Philosophers'', vii.</ref> was a [[Stoicism|Stoic philosopher]] who flourished around 140 BC. Two of his works: ''On the Voice'' ({{lang-el|Περὶ Φωνῆς}}) and ''On Elements'' ({{lang-el|Περὶ Στοιχείων}}), are mentioned by [[Diogenes Laërtius]].<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, ''Lives of Philosophers'', vii.</ref>

Archedemus is probably the same person as the Archedemus, whom [[Plutarch]] calls an [[Athens|Athenian]], and who, he states, went into [[Parthia]] and founded a school of Stoic philosophers at [[Babylon]].<ref>Plutarch, ''de Exilio'', 14.</ref>

Archedemus is also mentioned by [[Cicero]],<ref>Cicero, ''Acad. Quaest.'', ii. 47.</ref> [[Seneca the Younger|Seneca]],<ref>Seneca, ''Epistles'', 121.</ref> [[Epictetus]],<ref>Epictetus, ''Discourses'', Book II, Chapter 5.</ref> and other ancient writers.

