{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox Organization |name = Church of the Guanche People |image = Tanit-Symbol.svg |caption = The church's official symbol |type = Guanche ethnic [[neopaganism]] |region = Canary Islands, [[Spain]] |headquarters = [[San Cristóbal de La Laguna]] ([[Tenerife]], [[Canary Islands]], [[Spain]]). |formation = 2001 |website = [http://iglesiaguanche.blogspot.com.es/ Church of the Guanche People] }}
The '''Church of the Guanche People''' ({{lang-es|Iglesia del Pueblo Guanche}}) is a religious organisation, founded in 2001 in the city of [[San Cristóbal de La Laguna]], [[Tenerife]], [[Canary Islands]], [[Spain]]. It aims to perpetuate and spread the [[Traditional Berber religion|traditional religion]] of the ancient [[Guanches|Guanche]] people.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/502395/La_Iglesia_del_Pueblo_Guanche_consideraciones_metodologicas La Iglesia del Pueblo Guanche. Consideraciones metodológicas. Gobierno de Canarias.]</ref>
In 2008, the Church had approximately 300 members.<ref>Martin, Veronica (2008). [http://www.laopinion.es/secciones/noticia.jsp?pRef=2008100300_9_173826__Sociedad-canarios-profesa-religion-minoritaria 5% of Canarians profess a minority religion (Un 5% de canarios profesa una religión minoritaria)], ''La Opinión de Tenerife'' newspaper, 3 October.</ref> The Church of the Guanche People is included in the studies of minority religions in the Canary Islands.<ref>[http://www.observatorioreligion.es/upload/80/39/Pdfd_interactivo_Canarias.pdf Religiones entre continentes. Minorías religiosas en Canarias. Editado por la Universidad de La Laguna]</ref>
It was founded by a group of Canarian devotees of the goddess [[Chaxiraxi]].<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/502395/La_Iglesia_del_Pueblo_Guanche_consideraciones_metodologicas La Iglesia del Pueblo Guanche. Consideraciones metodológicas. Gobierno de Canarias.]</ref> The Church of the Guanche People performed [[baptism]]s and weddings according to what they know of Guanche custom. On 2002, a wedding held in accordance with purported Guanche rites took place on the island of Tenerife—a practice not observed for several centuries since the Spanish domination of the archipelago.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/502395/La_Iglesia_del_Pueblo_Guanche_consideraciones_metodologicas La Iglesia del Pueblo Guanche. Consideraciones metodológicas. Gobierno de Canarias.]</ref>
The Church of the Guanche People has its own [[liturgical calendar]], which officially begins with the first celebration of ''Achu n Magek'' in 2001. According to this system, this is the year I of the ''Guanche New Age''. 2018 would therefore be the year 18 on this calendar.<ref>[http://www.observatorioreligion.es/upload/80/39/Pdfd_interactivo_Canarias.pdf Religiones entre continentes. Minorías religiosas en Canarias. Editado por la Universidad de La Laguna]</ref>
The Church of the Guanche People is a [[Modern Paganism|modern pagan]] religious body representing Canarian Neopaganism.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/502395/La_Iglesia_del_Pueblo_Guanche_consideraciones_metodologicas La Iglesia del Pueblo Guanche. Consideraciones metodológicas. Gobierno de Canarias.]</ref>
