{{for|the Australian musician|James Wright Group}}
'''John Mathias Haffert''' ({{where|date=September 2012}} 23 August 1915 – {{where|date=September 2012}} 31 October 2001) was an American Roman Catholic author and editor. He wrote several books, mostly on Roman Catholic themes, co-founded Catholic societies, edited Catholic magazines and lectured on Catholic issues.

==Biography==
Haffert received his high school and college education at Mt. Carmel College, a Carmelite seminary, and then began his career as an author and lecturer.  Haffert was the co-founder of the [[Blue Army of Our Lady of Fatima]], a [[Roman Catholic Marian Society]] which was approved by [[Pope Pius XII]] and has about 25 million members worldwide.<ref>John Haffert, 1982 ''Dear Bishop, the History of the Blue Army'' AMI Press {{ISBN|0-911988-42-4}}</ref>  Haffert was assisted in the creation and Daily operations of Blue Army of Our Lady of Fatima by Father [[Venard Poslusney]].<ref>[http://valtorta.alphalink.com.au/POEM.HTM That Wonderful Poem]</ref>  He was the editor of "Scapular Magazine" which helped enroll one million Americans in the Blue Army of Our Lady of Fatima and in prayer for the Soviet Union.<ref>Eli Lederhendler, 2006 ''Jews, Catholics, and the Burden of History'' Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0-19-530491-8}}</ref>

Haffert was a strong advocate of the message of [[Our Lady of Fatima]] and he worked with Fatima visionary Sister [[Lucia dos Santos]] to develop the "Fatima Pledge" in 1946. This later became the "Blue Army Pledge", in 1948.<ref>[http://www.twoheartsdesign.com/jmh_obit.html On John Haffert's Life]</ref>  Haffert spoke often on topics concerning the [[Miracle of the Sun]].  One of Haffert's books, "That Wonderful Poem", endorses The [[Poem of the Man God]] by [[Maria Valtorta]], in which he explains how the Bishop of Fatima introduced him to these writings.

Haffert died at 86 in the United States.

