==Hinduism== A [[guru]] or sat guru in various traditions of [[Hinduism]] is given the name [[Dasa]],<ref>[http://www.hinduonnet.com/2000/09/07/stories/10070906.htm Able exponent of Dwaita philosophy] Thursday, September 07, 2000. [[The Hindu]]</ref> or "servant of God". A teacher also can be called ''uda ka das'', which means "the servant of God".<ref name="isbn1-4286-1308-0">{{cite book|author=|title=Essays And Lectures On The Religions Of The Hindus: Religious Sects of the Hindus V1|publisher=Kessinger Publishing, LLC|location=|year=2006|isbn=1-4286-1308-0|page=353}}</ref> In [[Sanskrit]], the word ''dasa'' ([[IAST]] ''{{IAST|dāsa}}'') means "servant," and this meaning is retained in all Indian languages where devotion to a [[personal God]] is practiced. In [[Tamil language|Tamil]], ''tontai'', ''dasa'', servant, or "slave," commonly are used to refer to devotees of Vishnu or Krishna.<ref name="isbn0-19-532639-3">{{cite book|author=Steven P. Hopkins|title=An ornament for jewels: love poems for the Lord of Gods|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2007|isbn=0-19-532639-3|page=160}}</ref> According to [[Gaudiya Vaishnava]] theology, as expressed in the [[Smriti]] statement ''{{IAST|dāsa-bhūto harer eva nānyasvaiva kadācana}}'', living entities (''bhuto'') are eternally in the service (''dasa'') of the Supreme Lord ([[Hari]]).<ref>[[Bhaktivedanta Swami]], A. C. (1972). ''The [[Bhagavad-gita As It Is]]'', second edition. [[New York City]]: [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]].</ref> Thus, designation for [[Vaishnavas]] was the status title ''[[dasa]]'' as part of their names, such as [[Haridasa|Hari dasa]], Narayana dasa, Ram das, Gopal das, etc.<ref name="Cynt01">{{cite book|author=Talbot, Cynthia|title=Precolonial India in practice: society, region, and identity in medieval Andhra|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2001|isbn=0-19-513661-6|page=81}}</ref>
